A simple model of environmental, social and governance investing is:=09Clim=
ate change represents an existential risk, and it is smart to invest in com=
panies that will do well in a lower-emissions world and avoid companies tha=
t will not survive the transition.=09Also investment managers have personal=
 moral views and decide not to invest in stuff they don=E2=80=99t like.[3]T=
he E in ESG is roughly a single thesis: Companies that create lots of carbo=
n emissions will not be able to do that forever, and so investing in compan=
ies that plan to do it forever is bad.[2] The S, however, generally has two=
 sides. Some people dislike different things from other people; some people=
  dislike the opposite=C2=A0things. Many=C2=A0important social questions ar=
e=C2=A0contested, and being engaged socially requires taking a side on thos=
e questions, not just being generically pro-social.[4]Anyway, if you are in=
 the business of producing weapons, last week you were not particularly ESG=
, but  this week you are very ESG:With a Russian invasion right on its door=
step, Europe now finds itself discussing whether weapons should be listed a=
s ESG assets, to grant them more favorable access to financing.The bloc is =
about to embark on the next stage of a taxonomy intended to define environm=
ental, social and governance investing rules. The Platform on Sustainable F=
inance -- a group convened by the European Union -- published its blueprint=
 for the kinds of activities that might be deemed socially sustainable on M=
onday. ...But with years to go before a social taxonomy is ready, lobbyists=
 are using what they see as a window of opportunity to try to shape the out=
come. According to BDSV, a German defense industry lobby group, Russia=E2=
=80=99s invasion of Ukraine last week is highly relevant to the question of=
 social sustainability in Europe.=E2=80=9CThe invasion of Ukraine shows how=
 important it is to have strong national defense,=E2=80=9D said Hans Christ=
oph Atzpodien, who runs BDSV. =E2=80=9CI appeal to the EU to recognize the =
defense industry as a positive contribution to =E2=80=98social sustainabili=
ty=E2=80=99 under the ESG taxonomy.=E2=80=9DMeanwhile, the defense industry=
 says it has struggled to get loans as ESG concerns steer funding in the fi=
nance sector. Rheinmetall AG Chief Executive Officer Armin Papperger told l=
ocal media in January that his firm had been cut off from credit by German =
lenders LBBW and BayernLB, due to their ESG concerns.=C2=A0The EU has previ=
ously signaled a willingness to listen to some of the defense industry=E2=
=80=99s arguments. In a policy paper earlier this month, the bloc underline=
d the importance of ensuring that =E2=80=9Cinitiatives on sustainable finan=
ce remain consistent with the European Union efforts to facilitate the Euro=
pean defense industry=E2=80=99s sufficient access to finance and investment=
.=E2=80=9DThere is something a bit strange about a bunch of governmental st=
andard-setters getting together to develop a =E2=80=9Csocial taxonomy=E2=80=
=9D over many years and then publishing it. Like, on the one hand, you are =
the governments; you can encourage or discourage activities through direct =
regulation rather than through this indirect method of encouraging ESG-focu=
sed private investors.On the other hand, ESG investing based on a rigid off=
icial taxonomy is itself weird. =E2=80=9CInvest in stuff that you think wil=
l make the world better and avoid stuff that you think will make it worse=
=E2=80=9D is a straightforward mission that makes obvious sense for many in=
vestors (not quite as obvious as =E2=80=9Cinvest in stuff that you think wi=
ll go up and avoid stuff that you think will go down,=E2=80=9D but related =
and in some ways better); it is also a flexible mission. =E2=80=9CLast week=
 I thought making weapons was bad but this week I think it is good=E2=80=9D=
 is a reasonably coherent thought so, sure, buy defense stocks. But will th=
at always be true?
