Okay, in entirely unrelated news, let=E2=80=99s do some insider trading hyp=
otheticals. I will ask some questions and sketch some answers (under my und=
erstanding of U.S. law), but my answers could be wrong and are certainly no=
t legal advice.=09I am some guy. I own 100 shares of Tesla Inc. stock. I de=
cide to sell them to pay for a kitchen renovation. I tell my brother. =E2=
=80=9CHey I=E2=80=99m gonna sell my Tesla stock,=E2=80=9D I say. He also ow=
ns Tesla stock. He decides to sell his stock too. He sells his stock before=
 I get around to selling mine. Did he commit insider trading? Did I? Let us=
 assume, for this hypothetical and all the others, that (1) I did not tell =
him that my plans to sell were a secret, (2) he said =E2=80=9Coh I might se=
ll too, is that okay,=E2=80=9D and (3) I said =E2=80=9Csure that=E2=80=99s =
fine.=E2=80=9D[5] I cannot imagine this being insider trading? I am just so=
me guy. There is no inside information.=09I am some really rich, famous guy=
. I own billions of dollars of Tesla stock. I decide to sell some of those =
shares to pay for a yacht. (Not all of them, or even most of them, and I=E2=
=80=99m still bullish on Tesla, but I=C2=A0need some cash for a yacht.) I s=
ell, say, $1 billion of stock. The stock declines over the course of my sel=
ling. When I finish, I tweet =E2=80=9Cjust sold $1 billion of Tesla stock t=
o buy a yacht, still bullish though,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and my thousands of Twit=
ter followers notice and the stock drops another, you know, 0.2% or whateve=
r. Did I commit insider trading? By selling stock=C2=A0before I told everyo=
ne else that I was going to sell? I think the answer here is still =E2=80=
=9Cabsolutely not.=E2=80=9D Sure my plans to sell were arguably material no=
npublic information (material because the stock did go down when I sold, no=
npublic because I knew about my plans before anyone else did), but they wer=
e=C2=A0my=C2=A0information; surely I don=E2=80=99t have to tell everyone el=
se my own plans before I trade on them? Insider trading, I like to say, is =
not about fairness, it=E2=80=99s about theft, and here I clearly am not usi=
ng anyone=E2=80=99s information illegitimately. I should say that some peop=
le, including at the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, find this ups=
etting, and have=C2=A0a vague sense that big investors should not be allowe=
d to trade when there is an =E2=80=9Cinformation asymmetry=E2=80=9D in whic=
h they know their plans and others don=E2=80=99t. But I think the law is pr=
etty clear here.=09Same as No. 2, but also I tell my brother before I trade=
, and he sells some stock, too, before I tweet about my sales. Again I know=
 and am fine with this. Is this insider trading? Here the question is perha=
ps more interesting. My selling is, again, arguably=C2=A0material nonpublic=
 information, and I have shared it with him and he has profited on it. But =
again, surely that information is mine to do what I want with? Neither my b=
rother nor I owe any Tesla investor any fiduciary duty not to trade on our =
own information about our own (or each other=E2=80=99s) intentions, do we? =
Assuming that I was fine with my brother trading, I think this is fine. But=
 people don=E2=80=99t like the answer to No. 2, and I think they=E2=80=99ll=
 like this one even less.[6]=09I am the chief executive officer and largest=
 shareholder of Tesla, and I decide to sell a few billion dollars=E2=80=99 =
worth of=C2=A0stock to do a weird reverse-psychology tax stunt while also p=
aying taxes on options exercise. Let us stipulate that I have absolutely no=
 material nonpublic information about Tesla=C2=A0when I decide to sell the =
stock; I am selling purely for my own stunt reasons, not because any bad ne=
ws is going to come out. I sell the stock, and then (1) tweet =E2=80=9CI so=
ld some stock=E2=80=9D and (2) file a public Form 4 disclosing my sales, wh=
ich SEC rules require me to file within  two days after selling. The stock =
goes down after this disclosure, because (1) selling a lot of stock moves t=
he price down and (2) people follow my moves closely and don=E2=80=99t like=
 when I sell. Did I commit insider trading? Again I think the answer is cle=
arly no; the SEC rules=C2=A0do=C2=A0require CEOs to disclose their sales (a=
nd I did), but only=C2=A0after=C2=A0they sell. So the fact that I sold with=
out disclosing it first is fine.[7] That said, this again is something that=
 makes people uncomfortable, and you sometimes see proposals to require (or=
 at least encourage) public-company executives to  pre-disclose their stock=
 sales.=C2=A0=09Same as No. 4, but also I tell my brother first, and he tra=
des.[8] Obviously if I told my brother =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99re announcin=
g bad earnings, dump your stock,=E2=80=9D that would be insider trading, bu=
t here the=C2=A0only=C2=A0information I have given him is about=C2=A0my own=
 personal intentions. He has gotten no material nonpublic information about=
 the company, only about my personal stock sales. And clearly=C2=A0I=C2=A0a=
m allowed to act on that information =E2=80=94=C2=A0I can sell stock when I=
 know I=E2=80=99m going to sell stock and no one else does =E2=80=94=C2=A0s=
o why can=E2=80=99t I also share it with my brother? And yet. I=C2=A0do=C2=
=A0have a fiduciary duty to Tesla shareholders, and my sales=C2=A0will=C2=
=A0drive down the price, so maybe telling my brother in advance is bad? I s=
till don=E2=80=99t think this is insider trading but I feel like people wil=
l disagree, and their disagreement won=E2=80=99t be crazy.=09Same as No. 5,=
 but also my brother is on the board of directors of Tesla. Again neither o=
f us has any secret bad news=C2=A0about Tesla=C2=A0that we=E2=80=99re hidin=
g. I=E2=80=99m just selling my stock for personal stunt reasons, and he=E2=
=80=99s selling his stock because he knows I=E2=80=99m selling mine. We=E2=
=80=99re just two brothers, talking about stock sales, same as in No. 1 rea=
lly. But now I have a fiduciary duty to Tesla shareholders, and=C2=A0he=C2=
=A0has a fiduciary duty to Tesla shareholders. He has come into some materi=
al nonpublic information (my stock-sale plans) that relates to Tesla (when =
I announce my sales the stock will go down), he is a fiduciary of Tesla, ca=
n he really trade? But of course the material nonpublic information is not =
exactly=C2=A0about=C2=A0Tesla, and he didn=E2=80=99t get it in the course o=
f his service as a Tesla director but rather in the course of his service a=
s my brother.[9] This one strikes me as hard! Like, I would not do that, pe=
rsonally, if I were the brother; it feels legally risky. But I am still not=
 sure it=E2=80=99s illegal.Anyway I have no idea what actually went on here=
 but if you assume the worst then you get to a really interesting legal gra=
y area:The Securities and Exchange Commission is investigating whether rece=
nt stock sales by Tesla Inc. Chief Executive Elon Musk and his brother, Kim=
bal Musk, violated insider-trading rules, according to people familiar with=
 the matter.The SEC=E2=80=99s investigation began last year after Kimbal Mu=
sk sold shares of Tesla valued at $108 million, one day before the Tesla ch=
ief polled Twitter users asking whether he should unload 10% of his stake i=
n the electric-car maker and pledging to abide by the vote=E2=80=99s result=
s.Elon Musk had framed the potential sale as a way to cover any taxes he wo=
uld need to pay if lawmakers imposed new taxes on unrealized capital gains.=
 He began selling billions of dollars worth of stock a few days after his t=
weet.Kimbal Musk sold 88,500 shares one day before the Tesla CEO tweeted ab=
out the potential sales of his own. The company=E2=80=99s shares fell sharp=
ly in the wake of Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s poll=E2=80=9458% of voters said he sho=
uld sell=E2=80=94indicating the tweet was viewed as negative news. =E2=80=
=A6Insider trading law historically covers the misuse or theft of informati=
on that belongs to a public company. Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s plans to trade, how=
ever, arguably belonged to him, and not to Tesla and its shareholders, said=
 Adam Pritchard, a law professor at the University of Michigan. In that cas=
e, it is unclear whether insider trading prohibitions would apply to Mr. Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s actions or to his brother=E2=80=99s trades, Mr. Pritchard said=
.=E2=80=9CWhat follows is that if the SEC wanted to pursue this, it would b=
e a hard-fought question in court,=E2=80=9D Mr. Pritchard said. =E2=80=9CIf=
 they decided to pursue it, Elon Musk would be willing to spend a little bi=
t to pursue it in court.=E2=80=9DMr. Musk told The Financial Times Thursday=
 that Kimbal Musk was unaware he planned to conduct the Twitter poll, while=
 the company=E2=80=99s lawyers did know about it.I=E2=80=99m sure the lawye=
rs were thrilled!
